claims:
1. A computer-implemented method for providing a patient-specific implant for a patient, the method comprising:
displaying, via at least one user device, a virtual three-dimensional model of at least a portion of the patient's spine for review by a user, wherein the virtual three-dimensional model is based on one or more images of the patient and is generated by a remote computing system;
transmitting, from the at least one user device, one or more design criteria associated with the virtual three-dimensional model;
receiving, from the remote computing system, a notification indicating that at least one of the design criteria is unacceptable;
transmitting, from the at least one user device, an alternative option from the user for the at least one unacceptable design criteria;
displaying, via the at least one user device, a modified virtual three-dimensional model of the patient's spine based on the alternative option from the user, wherein the modified virtual three-dimensional model is generated by the remote computing system; and
transmitting, from the at least one user device, user acceptance of the modified virtual three-dimensional model of the patient's spine so that the remote computing system designs a patient-specific implant that fits the modified virtual three-dimensional model of the patient's spine.
2. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising displaying one or more values for the patient's spine based on the modified virtual three-dimensional model of the patient's spine, wherein the one or more values indicate a configuration for the patient's spine.
3. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising receiving simulation data for the patient-specific implant being virtually implanted using the modified virtual three-dimensional model.
4. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising displaying a graphical user interface via an electronic screen of the at least one user device, wherein the graphical user interface provides one or more images of the modified virtual three-dimensional model of the patient's spine for review by the user.
5. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising displaying annotated spinal images associated with the patient's spine.
6. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising receiving, from a spine network of the remote computing system, abnormality analytics quantifying anatomical features of the patient.
7. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, further comprising:
receiving one or more values of the patient's spine; and
designing the patient-specific implant based on the one or more values.
